 @JayminStation  No, the manufacturers NEVER pay the tariffs. Tariffs are paid by the importer, who then pass the cost along to the vendor, who then pass the cost along to the consumer. Contrary to what some talking heads say. 
Tariffs are a tax on the consumer, NOT the manufacturer.
They say the whole idea is to provide relief or fair competition to domestic manufacturers, but the fact of the matter is we do not have any domestic manufacturers making these cards. And no manufacturer is going to build any factories to make these in the US. Why should they? The build them for whatever they charge, they do not pay the tariffs, we do. They will not lose market share unless people actually stop buying them. So in the end. This is a money grab by the government to take money from you!

 @dcso4080  Get this, here is another way you are getting nailed by tariffs. If the price of something was $100 before tariffs. the price then goes up to $125.  So you are paying sales tax on the $125, not the $100. SO you pay the increased price for the Tariffs, but also the increased sales tax.
And yes there are many vendors who will add a little more on top of the tariff. They will charge what the market will pay. 
The only way prices go down is if the consumer will not buy the product at the current price. That is capitalism 101
